se the static field initializes in the image heap after the JVM test. Hold on, might the native test executable include the image heap state from the build? During the native-image compile, it executes class initializers, but for classes without `<clinit>`, static fields default to null. Could I call `findAncestorWithClass` in a test method that dynamically loads the class using `Class.forName`?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Checking JVM behavior**\\n\\nI’m looking into the JVM specification regarding class loading. It seems that loading a class doesn’t automatically load its superinterfaces, right? But, since I'm creating a new SimpleTagSupport, it’s likely that the superinterfaces are loaded. However, I can't ignore the synthetic class target being JspTag. That seems impossible to avoid loading. Yet, I wonder if Java’s Class.forName call might still work. I'm also wondering if the agent records whether it was loaded or not.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Formulating code updates**\\n\\nI’m working on the next patch for SimpleTagSupportTest. First, I should remove the `JspTag` variable type import and replace it with `Object ancestor`. Then, I’ll create two tests: the first one should verify that `findAncestorWithClassInitializesJspTagTypeCheckAndReturnsNearestAncestor` can accept `SimpleTagSupport.class` since it makes sense to use that instead of `JspTag.class`. Lastly, I want to add a custom interface marker along with a subclass that implements this marker.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_eRSoyRdmqCzhM2xbIgYCq3s2|fc_04ca318d0ca906c2016a27671ffb1481969ed388661128cb5f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); cd $tmp; curl -sSLO https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/jspapi/jsp-api/2.0-20040521/jsp-api-2.0-20040521.jar; javap -classpath jsp-api-2.0-20040521.jar -p javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.TagAdapter javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.SimpleTag javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.JspTag | sed -n '1,200p'", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-